Psiphon statistics indicate growth in hourly connections during the blocking period of up to 25 times baseline usage.

<img src="<%= @relativeToRoot '/images/blog/UG_22_feb_traffic.png' %>" alt="Uganda traffic over the Psiphon network increased 25 times over baseline usage during the blocking period" class="img-responsive center-block">

Psiphon’s involvement has received ongoing coverage including the online newspaper [The Daily Dot](http://www.dailydot.com/politics/uganda-isp-election-censorship/). In an interview, CEO Karl Kathuria [told Smartmonkey TV](http://www.smartmonkeytv.com/channel/newsletters/musevenis_ban_on_social_media_in_uganda_the_good_news_and_the_bad_news_for) “before the shutdown we had a very low number of users in Uganda. After the shutdown, those who knew about our software started posting about it and there was a big jump on our network... it will go up again much faster next time.”

The case demonstrates that in response to censorship, blocking, and other restrictions, internet users will turn to known tools that connect them to content and to each other.

